04330nam a22005415i 9780300274912DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803002749127 a10.12987/97803002749122doi  a(DE-B1597)666723  a(OCoLC)1393242466  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 7aPOL0090002bisacsh04a338.951223/swe1 aHuang, Yasheng, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Rise and Fall of the EAST :bHow Exams, Autocracy, Stability, and Technology Brought China Success, and Why They Might Lead to Its Decline /cYasheng Huang. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (440 p.) :b8 b-w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: Unpacking the EAST Formulation -- tPart I Examination -- t1. Keju as a Scaling Instrument -- t2. Organizing China—and the CCP -- tPart II Autocracy -- t3. A State without a Society -- t4. Reversion to the Autocratic Mean -- tPart III Stability -- t5. What Makes Chinese Autocracy So Stable? -- t6. Tullock’s Curse -- tPart IV Technology -- t7. Reframing the Needham Question -- t8. A Republic of Government -- tPart V The Future of the EAST Model -- t9. The CCP of Xi Jinping -- t10. Breaking Out of the EAST Model? -- tChronology -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe long history of China’s relationship between stability, diversity, and prosperity, and how its current leadership threatens this delicate balance Chinese society has been shaped by the interplay of the EAST—exams, autocracy, stability, and technology—from ancient times through the present. Beginning with the Sui dynasty’s introduction of the civil service exam, known as Keju, in 587 CE—and continuing through the personnel management system used by the Chinese Communist Party (CCP)—Chinese autocracies have developed exceptional tools for homogenizing ideas, norms, and practices. But this uniformity came with a huge downside: stifled creativity. Yasheng Huang shows how China transitioned from dynamism to extreme stagnation after the Keju was instituted. China’s most prosperous periods, such as during the Tang dynasty (618–907) and under the reformist CCP, occurred when its emphasis on scale (the size of bureaucracy) was balanced with scope (diversity of ideas). Considering China’s remarkable success over the past half-century, Huang sees signs of danger in the political and economic reversals under Xi Jinping. The CCP has again vaulted conformity above new ideas, reverting to the Keju model that eventually led to technological decline. It is a lesson from China’s own history, Huang argues, that Chinese leaders would be wise to take seriously.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBureaucracyxEconomic aspectszChinaxHistory. 0aChinaxEconomic conditions. 0aCivil servicezChinaxExaminationsxHistory. 0aEconomic developmentzChinaxHistory. 0aIndustrial policyzChinaxHistory. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Comparative Politics.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311074978640uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/9780300274912?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300274912423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300274912/original  a978-3-11-074978-6  Yale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles